<subSubSection pageId="303" pageNumber="304" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="303.[151,1437,1341,1945]" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1737,1764]" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Machado &amp; Oswald, 2020" authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" box="[341,615,1738,1764]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Riekoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="303" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longitudinalis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[341,615,1738,1764]" italics="true" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">Riekoleon longitudinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[620,709,1738,1764]" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[620,709,1738,1764]" pageId="303" pageNumber="304" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is the largest species in the genus based on forewing length and is easily identified by the dark longitudinal lines of the forewing and pronotum. The short pronotal setae, and large and rectangular female posterior gonapophysis place this species close to 
<taxonomicName box="[935,1034,1810,1836]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Riekoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="303" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rudda">
<emphasis box="[935,1034,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">R. rudda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The shape of the dark longitudinal line of the forewing is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Tillyard" baseAuthorityYear="1916" box="[526,872,1846,1873]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Austrogymnocnemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="303" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berthoudi">
<emphasis box="[526,872,1846,1873]" italics="true" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">Austrogymnocnemia berthoudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the large apical spots in the hind wing (of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Riekoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="303" pageNumber="304" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longitudinalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">R. longitudinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the general form of the female terminalia clearly separate them. For phylogenetic relationships see 
<figureCitation box="[194,262,1918,1944]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,348,1348]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1436,345,1348]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 4. Strict consensus tree of morphology-based parsimony analysis of species belonging to the former subtribe Periclystina (ingroup, names in black), and outgroups (names in red). Former Glenoleon species are shown on blue branches, former Austrogymnocnemia species on green branches. Numbers above branches are Bremer support values; numbers below branches are bootstrap values (shown where&gt;50%)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3896822" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3896822/files/figure.png" pageId="303" pageNumber="304">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
